# PolyForm Noncommercial License 1.0.0

<https://polyformproject.org/licenses/noncommercial/1.0.0>

## About This License

This license adds a single prohibition for commercial use to the terms of the
PolyForm Perimeter License 1.0.0, which is itself adapted from the Bitverse
Perimeter License. See [polyformproject.org][P] for more information.

[P]: https://polyformproject.org/licenses/noncommercial/1.0.0

## Purpose

This license lets you use the software for free, for any use that doesn't
generate revenue, and asks that you share changes you make with the developer.
You have to ask for a separate, paid license if you want to use the software in
or for a business that earns or sends you money.

## License Terms

### Copyright License

The licensor grants you a copyright license to do everything with the software
that copyright law lets you do, subject to the license terms below.  Copyright
law, among other things, gives the licensor exclusive control over copying,
distributing, and changing the software, as well as applying it to create new
works.

### Patent License

The licensor grants you a patent license to do everything with the software
that patent law lets you do, subject to the license terms below.  Patent law,
among other things, gives the licensor exclusive control over making, using,
and selling the software.

### Notice

If you receive the software, you must give anyone else to whom you give the
software a copy of these license terms.  If you make changes to the software,
you must include a prominent notice in the software, or in a documentation or
readme file, identifying that you changed the software, and giving your contact
information.  You may not remove or alter any license or copyright notice that
the licensor included in the software.

### Changes

The licensor grants you a broad license to make and share changes to the
software.  You can share your changes however you want, for any noncommercial
purpose.

### No Commercial Use

The license terms below do not allow any commercial use of the software.  The
licensor may license the software commercially, and expect you to pay for a
license.

### Reliability

The licensor offers no warranty, representation, or guarantee of any kind.
  The licensor disclaims any liability for loss or damage you suffer in
  connection with using the software or any changes to it.

### Trademark

The license terms do not give you any right to use the licensor's trademarks.

### Other Licenses

The license terms do not cover any software that the licensor did not license
to you.  For example, if the software depends on other open-source or
commercially licensed software, you are responsible for satisfying the license
terms of that other software.

### Termination

If you do not follow the license terms, your license ends.  Your license ends
automatically and immediately if you:

  1. fail any attempt to follow the license terms

  2. use the software commercially, even if only once

  3. challenge the validity of any license term or copyright notice in the
     software, or any of the licensor's rights to the software

  4. fail to pay any commercial license fee you owe to the licensor

The licensor can end your license for any other reason, by telling you that
your license has ended.

## Definitions

### Software

"Software" means all the software that the licensor licenses to you under
these license terms.

### Commercial Use

"Commercial use" means any use of the software that earns or sends you, or
any third party, money, or that you use to pay for any other work, product, or
service.  Examples of commercial use:

  1. You use the software to offer a paid service.

  2. You use the software to offer a free service that depends on other
     revenue, such as advertising.

  3. You use the software to build things that you sell.

  4. You use the software to run or support a business.

  5. You use the software to develop other software that you sell.

  6. You make and sell things using the software.

  7. You make changes to the software, sell or license them, and keep the
     proceeds.

  8. You allow any third party to pay you for use of the software.

Noncommercial use does not include any of the above, or earning or sending
revenue to any third party to support any of the above.  For example, if you
receive the software for free, and make money using it, but pay all proceeds
to a charity, that is still commercial use.